Every year on April 1, the Truans, along with many other local families, could get permission to simply hitch up a horse and tow their chalet on to the seaside dunes at Riviere Towans in St Ives Bay for the summer season. 

In 1926 the chalet was the first to be given a permanent fixed and anchored position in the dunes where it remains today. Now the little hut, the oldest still existing on Riviere Towans, is up for sale and is expected to fetch at least £80,000. 

A reminder of a bygone age, it is largely untouched from the time it was purchased for £10 in 1924, say selling agents Driftwood Properties.

It might be small, but a bit like Doctor Who's Tardis, appearances can be deceptive for inside it has two bedrooms, a hall and a toilet extension. 

