Over the years the Truans added extensions for sleeping accommodation and toilet facilities, adding electricity in the 1950s - another first - and cladding a decade later.

During the war years, trenches were dug outside its door, and later more chalets were built around it and larger holiday companies arrived in St Ives Bay. 

Original features dating back to 1924 include the doors, windows, a Belfast sink and a meat safe. It has a living room, two bedrooms and an attached outside toilet cubicle. 

